    <p class="text-gray-300">Finally, we are left with the event  <span class="math">e_1</span> , namely that  <span class="math">m_{2\\cdot h - 1}&#x27; = m_{2\\cdot h - 1}</span> . Although it is not a given that an adversary will be able to turn this event into a forgery, we are generously granting a win regardless. We will assume that  <span class="math">c_{2\\cdot h - 1}&#x27; \\neq c_{2\\cdot h - 1}</span> , because otherwise the event  <span class="math">e_1</span>  is not possible (by inspection). Our assumption implies that the  <span class="math">\\widetilde{\\mathsf{R}}^{(\\mathsf{N},2\\cdot \\mathsf{h})}(c_{2\\cdot h - 1}&#x27;)</span>  call is fresh, and since it needs to hit a unique value in order for  <span class="math">e_1</span>  to occur,  <span class="math">e_1</span>  happens with probability  <span class="math">1 / p</span> .</p>

