    <p class="text-gray-300">In Table 5 we present the online costs, as a function of  <span class="math">\\ell</span>  for our various constructions. For each variant we give the number of rounds and the number of openings. As we have selected highly parallel modes of operation, the round complexity does not depend on the message length. Intuitively, the online round complexity should define the latency of a protocol and the online opening complexity should define the throughput. However, due to the nature of actual physical networks we expect that as soon as we reach the maximum capacity of the network, in terms of data sent (i.e. openings) per round, the latency will drop off rapidly. Thus as  <span class="math">\\ell</span>  increases we expect to see an increase in latency, despite latency "theoretically" being a constant. The key question is then how big does  <span class="math">\\ell</span>  need to be before the latency for a specific PRF and mode decreases linearly in  <span class="math">\\ell</span> ?</p>

